The pilot’s inadequate compensation for the prevailing wind conditions, which resulted in a loss of control during landing.
The pilots’ failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during the landing.
NA

NA
The pilot’s failure to store the nose landing gear securing bar within reach in the cabin, which resulted in a nose gear collapse following a manual landing gear extension.
The pilot’s failure to maintain control of the airplane during an attempted go-around, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall and impact with the runway.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control of the airplane while landing in crosswind conditions, which resulted in a runway excursion.
The pilot’s decision to continue the approach to land in conditions where he was unable to see in front of the airplane due to sun glare, which resulted in in a collision a building.

Improper maintenance of the fuel injector nozzles and the pilots’ failure to abort the takeoff during the takeoff roll. Contributing to the accident was the mechanic’s decision to return the airplane to service with the engine unable to attain its full rated power.
The pilot’s failure to see and avoid power lines while maneuvering at low altitude.
The flight instructor’s failure to maintain control of the helicopter during the takeoff, which resulted in a dynamic rollover.

The pilot’s failure to secure and feather the left engine and increase power on the right engine after a perceived loss of engine power in the left engine, which resulted in a loss of control and impact with terrain just short of the runway. Contributing to the accident was a reduction in engine power from the left engine due to a 1st stage turbine blade midspan separation and material loss in the 2nd stage stator that were the result of engine operation at high temperatures for an extended period of time.
The balloon pilot’s delay in relighting the burner, which resulted in a hard landing and his ejection from the balloon.
The passenger’s decision to continue an unstable approach while at low altitude and in proximity to a known obstacle, which resulted in a collision with power lines.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during the landing in a crosswind condition, which resulted in a runway excursion.
The instructor’s multiple applications of the airplane’s brakes during high-speed taxi over a short duration, which overheated and ignited the right main landing gear wheel brake assembly.
The pilot’s failure to maintain adequate clearance from trees during an approach in sun glare and hazy conditions.
A total loss of engine power due to oil starvation of the No. 1 cylinder. Contributing to the accident was the pinched No. 1 cylinder oil injection line.
The pilot’s improper landing flare, which resulted in a hard, bounced landing and the nose landing gear collapsing.
The pilot's failure to maintain airspeed while landing with a quartering tailwind, which resulted in a loss of control and a hard landing.
The pilot's improper landing flare in crosswind conditions, which resulted in a bounced landing, and his subsequent failure to maintain directional control, which resulted in a ground-loop.
The pilot's incapacitation during the takeoff roll due to a stroke.
The arcing failure of the windshield heat L2 power wire on the right windshield due to unknown reasons.
The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing, which resulted in a runway excursion and impact with a ditch.
The student pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing with a crosswind, which resulted in a runway excursion and impact with approach lights.
The helicopter’s collision with a bird during cruise flight.
